===Etymology===
From a merger of two words:
* {{inh|en|enm|shutel}}, {{m|enm|shotel}}, {{m|enm|schetel}}, {{m|enm|schettell}}, {{m|enm|schyttyl}}, {{m|enm|scutel|t=bar; bolt}}, from {{inh|en|ang|sċyttel}}, {{m|ang|sċutel|t=bar; bolt}}, equivalent to {{suffix|en|shut|le}}
* {{inh|en|enm|shutel}}, {{m|enm|schetil}}, {{m|enm|shotil}}, {{m|enm|shetel}}, {{m|enm|schootyll}}, {{m|enm|shutyll}}, {{m|enm|schytle}}, {{m|enm|scytyl|t=missile; projectile; spear}}, from {{inh|en|ang|sċytel}}, {{m|ang|sċutel|t=dart, arrow}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*skutilaz}}.
The name for a loom weaving instrument, recorded from 1338, is from a sense of being "shot" across the threads. The back-and-forth imagery inspired the extension to "passenger trains" in 1895, aircraft in 1942, and spacecraft in 1969, as well as older terms such as {{m|en|shuttlecock}}.

